div.p:
               HAving been present at some of those late Conferences (that I may not call them Disputes) which have been had publikely betwixt your self and some others about your Doctrine and Practise, I have found no satisfaction at all from them concerning either, though they were admitted on purpose to satisfie any man that was contrary minded, as you have declared, and not for your conviction, though upon supposall you were in an Error; (which certainly, you that crie out so vehemently against Infallibility in Synods, Classes, &c. must give men leave to suppose till they know why one man may not erre as well as an hundred.) You professe Disputes shall not move you, having perfect rest in your spirit, and full satisfaction already in every point that you hold, and in all things which you practise. And truly Sir, had other men who love the truth and wayes of God as well as your self, the like satisfaction, they would not grutch your successe at all, but rejoyce if the gleanings of Anabaptisme were greater then the vintage of any other way or profession whatsoever; till then, you must not be angry if they reckon the way you go in, amongst the first-born of the abhorrings of their souls;
Jer. 6.16. they cannot but look at it as none of the good old way, but as a path utterly untrodden by the feet of Gods people, till of late some have unhappily turned aside to it; neither can they but look at those Errors which lead you along in it, as Errors of the first magnitude. Suffer me therefore, Sir, who am in the number of these unsatisfied ones, to ease my thoughts of your way a little by giving them vent into some few Quaeres, both as a short Essay towards the tryall of your grounds, and as a testimony

to the truths and wayes of God as well as against the unheedinesse of your wayes, by reason of which the way of truth is evill spoken of.

This cannot be from the Apostles scope in that Chapter which is mainly to prove that the rejection of the Jewes is not irrecoverable; 
                  Answ. 
                and one argument that he uses in the proof of this laid downe ver. 16. is, if the root be holy, so are the branches;
               Rom. 11.16. now this root must needs be the Covenant or God or their holy Ancestors who derived inlike sort holines to them, as the first fruits being holy derive holinesse (by Gods institution) to the whole lump, and as the root being holy, deriveth holinesse (by Gods Covenant) to the branches; or else he misseth the scope in his Argument, which is to shew that the Jewes shall be ingrassed into Christ, and become holy, because their root is holy; which will strongly follow, if we take Abraham, or the Covenant of God with Abraham and his seed for the root, but not if Christ be taken for the root; this is good arguing, if Abraham, or the Covenant of God with him and his seed be holy, then the Jewes (although now broken off) are or shall be holy also, for Christ imparts his holinesse to none but such as are actually in him by Faith; but the Covenant of God or our holy Ancestors may derive a federall holinesse to their seed, though not actually in Christ; else the Apostles Argument touches not, much more shall these which be natural branches be graffed into their own Olive-tree, verse 24. and if it did not, how are

the unbelieving Jewes beloved for their Fathers sakes? ver. 28.
